area_description_data.5: In recent years, some wealthy Hartford citizens began buying up large acreages and building thereon patalial mansions- one even has a gold course on the front lawn. Only occasionally is there found a dwelling that is not extremely large. On High Farms Road there has been a small, speculative development of the highest order but here the grounds are not extensive and houses are built fairly close together. Because of stability of owners, mortgagees look with favor on this section although it is recognized that there is neither sales nor rentral market for this type of property. A wide arterial highway seperates this area from its less desirable neighbor.
area_description_data.1a: Wooded hillside land rising steeply to the west giving beaitful view of the city.
area_description_data.1c: Distances from center of city, schools, churches and stores as well as lack of all improvements.

area_description_data.5: A section opened up a few years ago by a number of speculative developers and one which is growing more rapidly than any other. It is the most desirable residential area for those seeking modest sized dwellings. Architecture is varied but exceptionally pleasing and though most plots are small, they are well kept. House ownership is high, the only rentals being a comparatively few, newly built homes which remain unsold. Although this area is a favorite with lenders, caution is exercised as some of the new construction is known to be "jerry" built. To the east, a stream separates this section from its less desirable neighborhood.
area_description_data.1c: Distrance from business section of Hartford

area_description_data.5: A more recent development, largely of a speculative nature, to provide most desirable homes in the upper-middles brackets. Design is varied but altogether pleasing. Plots are not large but well laid out and well maintained. Pride of ownership is everywhere evident. Lenders look with particular favor on this area.
area_description_data.1c: None.

area_description_data.5: A continuation of Hartford's most desirable residential section containing only homes in the highest brackets. It was begun by wealthy individuals for their own occupancy but speculative developers have recently opened up many streets in the upper western portion with houses of the same high character. Dwellings are very karge abd if varied but attractive architecture. Grounds are extensive and beautifully landscaped and maintained. Lenders recognize stability of owners but are aware of the impossibility of either selling or renting properties on a satisfactory basis.
area_description_data.1a: High, rolling and wooded land with pleasant outlook.
area_description_data.1c: None,

area_description_data.5: This is a sparsely settled area still largely composed of farms. In recent years, there has been a tendency to purchase older homes and completely renovate and modernize them. This has lead to the establishment of a number of large estates and, where land was cheap, to the construction of small modern homes. The variation is so great as to preclude any attempts at classification.

A sparsely improved section, the present use of which is still largely devoted to farms. There has been a recent tendency toward the purchase of large tracts which have been turned into estates and erection thereon of sizable mansions. Some of the new construction, however, has been of more modest nature. Extreme variation prevents proper classification.
area_description_data.1a: Wooded land rising from the river

area_description_data.5: Hartford's most desirable residential section. An area containing large, palatial homes of many of the wealthiest citizens. Grounds are spacious, most attractively landscaped and maintained in excellent condition. Although lenders appreciate stability of owners, they acknoeledge the impossibility of either selling or renting such properties on satisfactory basis.
area_description_data.1a: Generally wooded land rising quite sharply from the river and with pleasing outlook.
area_description_data.1b: Accessibility as wella s attractiveness of location and its improvements.
area_description_data.1c: None

area_description_data.5: A small, new and, as yet, sparsely  developed section containing not over 8 or 10 well built and attractively designed homes. Lots are of fair size, well landscaped and evidence a marked pride of ownership. This is the most desirable area for those who must reside in East Hartford
area_description_data.1c: Lack of all improvements and sitrance from schools , churches, stores, etc.

area_description_data.5: A newer and, for thet most part, speculative development which still continues at a fairly rapid pace. Dwellings are of modest size located upon small plots which are well cared for. Some of the new construction is of exceptionally attractive design. Favorite section among lenderes it is, nevertjeless, eported that some of the new development is overprices and some "jerry" built. As a whole, are rates a high "blue".
area_description_data.1a: Land is slightly rolling and wooded in portions
area_description_data.1b: Convenient to small centrally located shopping center.
area_description_data.1c: Distance from buiness section of Hartford

area_description_data.5: A slightly older section which has slowed up somewhat in its development but still retains its desirability. Architecture is substantially similar and not as attractive as in the newer area. Plots are fairly small giving the air of some congestion. Pride of ownership is generally evident, Lenders look up this as a sound mortgage section.
area_description_data.1b: Attractive location and convenient to serveral,small, local shopping centers.
area_description_data.1c: None

area_description_data.5: Formerly one of Hartford's best residential sections but age of structures now detracts from desirability. Homes are of fair size- some quite large - and stand on proportionate plots eliminating any air of congestion. Pride of ownership is quite evident.
area_description_data.1a: Land rises slightly to the west
area_description_data.1c: Age of structures and influx of better grade apartments.

area_description_data.5: A newer development of attractively designed, singles family homes with an internmingling of some two family and "boston" duplexes. Though plots are small, there are well laid out and give teh appearance of having good care. Because of stability of owner and both marketability and rentability of properties, this area is one of the favorites among lenders.
area_description_data.1c: Distance to business and shopping centers and not overly good transportation.

area_description_data.5: A somewhat newer section which extends into the Town of Bloodfield. It is largely given over to teh Hebrew race although the better class Italians are now also moving there. Architecture is not overly pleasing and lack variety. Plots are small giving the appearance of some gestion. Though some dwellings are more desirable than the average and show pride of ownership, the area as a whole rates a low "Blue".
area_description_data.1a: In the west, ridgeland sloping to the east and west. In the east, land rises from the lowland adjacent to the river.
area_description_data.1b: An attractive location with outlook over the park.
area_description_data.1c: Slightly inconvenient to business section and not too good transportation facilities.

area_description_data.5: Three fairly new and similar areas containing modest sized homes of somewhat varied architecture. Plots are in proportion, well maintained and generally evidence pride of ownership. The two western sections are subject to floods but only during periods of unusually high water.
area_description_data.1c: In two western portions, danger of flooding is acute is times of very high water.
area_description_data.2a: White collar and small business men

area_description_data.5: An area which, unfortunately, got away to a poor start. Homes vary from summer bungalows to those of fair size, which land in proportion. Architecture is anything but pleasing and many dwellings seem badly in need of paint. As pride of ownership seems quite lacking, the section rates a low "Yellow".
area_description_data.1a: Hillside and wooded land rising steeply to the west
area_description_data.1c: Character of development, distance from schools, churches, stores and center of Hartford as well as lack if all city improvements

area_description_data.5: A somewhat older section of workingmen's homes where doubles and singles predominate, save south of Brewer Street where only one family homes are found.  Dwellings are similar and not overly attractive architecture, are located on fair sized plots but evidence only spotty pride of ownership. Near the aviation field there is a twenty-four hour din from the testing of motors and in the north constant smoke from the railroad yards. As a whole, the area rates a low "yellow"
area_description_data.1a: Land rises slightly from the river and becomes rolling and wooded in parts.
area_description_data.1b: Fair accessibility to places of employment
area_description_data.1c: Near aviation field with noise from tasting motors. Also near railroad yards with subsequent dirt and smoke.
area_description_data.3c: Up to 60 Up to 60 Up to 60

area_description_data.5: A newer section confinded to workingmen's homes. Architecture of dwellings is neither varied nor overly pleasing. Plots are small but not so much so as to give the impressive of congestion. This isa favorite with the lenders because of stability of income of woners and ready saleability or rentability of properties. The entire northern portion rates a "a high yellow." In the southern portion there are some scattered plants and, while generally similiar, rates a low "Yello".
area_description_data.1a: Rolling land which is wooded in parts.
area_description_data.1c: Cheapness of construction and chracter of development

area_description_data.5: The continuation of an older and quite congested residential section of Hartford. With an indicated trend to apartments, there is a decline in desirability from a private house standpoint and lenders exercise care in any lending operations.
area_description_data.1b: Conveniences to center of Hartford and places of employment.
area_description_data.1c: Age and obsoleacences of building
area_description_data.3b: Frame and brick Frame Frame and brick

area_description_data.5: A slightly older section of unattractively designed workingmen's home. In the built up section plots are generally small giving the atmosphere of congestion. Pride of ownership is decidedly spotty and the area rates a low "Yellow".
area_description_data.1b: Attraction ot working men employed in nearby plants.
area_description_data.1c: Character of improvement and neighorhood plus inacccessiblity to the center of Hartford.

area_description_data.5: An older and quite congested residential section of the city. In the eastern portion there are still a number of fine, old homes still maintained by first families but with their passing these are gradually giving way to apartment houses. Because of this trend, caustion is advised in making loans.
area_description_data.1b: Convenient to places of employment and center of city.
area_description_data.1c: Age of obsolescence of buildings and trend to apartments in the eastern portion
area_description_data.3b: Frame and brick Frame Frame and brick

area_description_data.5: A number of years ago, this was the city's best residential section and contained a number of fine, old homes of leading families. Age and obsolecence set in and many have been altered into either small aprtments or rooming houses. Others have been replaced by modern apartments which is particularly practicable owing to the large size of the lots.
area_description_data.1c: Age and obsolescence of dwellings and trend toward apartments and rooming house
area_description_data.3b: Brick and frame Brick Brick and frame

area_description_data.5: An older section of the city which has been developed with an unattractive type of workingmen's home, Two and three family dwellings redominate and tehre are a lesser numner of singles with a scattering of multi-family. Plots are narrow giving a somwhat congested appearance and pride of ownership is decidedly spotty. It is worthy of a note that some singles are above the average.
area_description_data.1b: Accessability to places of employment and center of city
area_description_data.1c: Chracter of neighborhood
area_description_data.3b: Frame Brick and frame Brick and frame

area_description_data.5: A very old and congested portion of the city in which dwellings include all from singles to multi-family. A number of the large, old, one-family homes have been converted into small flats and rooming houses. Many of the twos and thress contain stores on the ground floor. Throughout the area there are scattered manufacturing plants. Owing to recent purchases by the State, property values along Washington Street have risen. As a whole, the section rates a low "Yellow" and lenders exercise utmost caution.
area_description_data.1b: Nearness to places of employment and center for Hartford.
area_description_data.1c: Age and obsolescence of structures and encroachment of both business and industry.

area_description_data.5: A somewhat older section of workingmen's homes where doubles predominate and which have been erected on fairly narrow plots giving, in most portions, an air of congestion. Architectire is neither varied nor particularly pleasing and pride of ownership is decidedly spotty. The Negro families are confined to Roosevelt Street. Lenders suggest caution is in the selection of loans.
area_description_data.1b: Attractive to wroking men because of type of habitation.
area_description_data.1c: Character of improvement and neighborhood. In the southern portion, inaccessibility.

area_description_data.5: The city's oldest residential section which has gradually drifted into slum area now mainly occupied by Negros.It is a very congested neighborhood containing scattered plants and a variation in type of dwelling from small singles to multi-family with prices largely theoretical in view of the many tax and sacrifice sales. South of the railroad, are found combination stores and dwellings and this portion, as well as along the eastern boundary, is particularlrly subject to floods. There has been a sizeable amount of demolition on the part of institutional holderns and they will no longer lend in this section.
area_description_data.1a: Land slopes toward the river where it is subject to floods in time of high water.
area_description_data.1c: A slum area.
area_description_data.3b: Brick and frame Brick and frame Frame
area_description_data.3c: Up to 70 Up to 70 Up to 70

area_description_data.5: An old and congested section of the city where both business and scattered factories are mixed in with every type of dwelling of which multi-family predominates. Notwithstanding that much of the area is subject of the floods there has been a substantial amount rehabilitation. The cit has purchased the swampland south of Wawarame Avenue in order to eliminate dumps and shacks. Institutional owners have modernized many of the old multi-family tenements. The experience of lenders has been anything but satisfactory.
area_description_data.1a: Generalyl low land sloping to the river where property is subject to floods
area_description_data.1c: Character of neighborhood and inhabitant plus encroachment of business and industry
area_description_data.3c: Up to 70 Up to 70 Up to 70

area_description_data.5: The three sections bordering the river are regularly subject to floods each year which the inhabitants seems to like for it fertilizes their small gardens. In the northeastern section there is no danger from the floods but the area sufferes from the soot from the railroad yards. Dwellings throughout the area include everything from shacks to two-family and an occasionally triple. All are in poor condition and evidence no pride of ownernship. The entire area is shunned by lenders and many be classed as "hazardous".
area_description_data.1a: In the west land is very low. In the east, it is flat nd higher.
area_description_data.1c: Subject to floods in west and smoke and dirt from railroads in the east.
area_description_data.3c: Up to 40 Up to 40 Up to 40
